  <p>We're going to do something uncomfortable. We're going to calculate exactly how much money you're losing from <a href="/blog/why-tradesmen-lose-jobs">missed calls</a>. Not a vague estimate — the actual maths, applied to your trade.</p>

  <p><strong>Fair warning: the numbers are bigger than you think.</strong></p>

  <h2>The Formula</h2>

  <p>The calculation is straightforward:</p>

  <p style="text-align: center; font-size: 1.25rem; font-weight: 700; padding: 1.5rem; background: var(--color-surface); border-radius: 0.75rem; border: 1px solid var(--color-border-subtle);">
    Missed calls per week × % that are genuine enquiries × conversion rate × average job value = <strong>Lost revenue per week</strong>
  </p>

  <p>Let's run the numbers for different scenarios.</p>

  <h2>Scenario 1: "I Only Miss A Couple Of Calls"</h2>

  <p>You think you only miss two or three calls a week. You're probably being optimistic — most tradesmen underestimate their missed calls by half — but let's use your number.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Missed calls: <strong>3 per week</strong></li>
    <li>Genuine new enquiries: <strong>50%</strong> (1.5 calls)</li>
    <li>Would have converted: <strong>60%</strong> (0.9 jobs)</li>
    <li>Average job value: <strong>£350</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Lost revenue: £315 per week. £16,380 per year.</strong></p>

  <p>That's a decent used van. A family holiday. A year's worth of materials. Gone, because three calls went to voicemail.</p>

  <h2>Scenario 2: "I'm Busy, I Miss Quite A Few"</h2>

  <p>You're on jobs from 8am to 5pm most days. You're honest with yourself — you probably miss five to eight calls a day during busy periods.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Missed calls: <strong>8 per week</strong></li>
    <li>Genuine new enquiries: <strong>50%</strong> (4 calls)</li>
    <li>Would have converted: <strong>60%</strong> (2.4 jobs)</li>
    <li>Average job value: <strong>£350</strong></li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Lost revenue: £840 per week. £43,680 per year.</strong></p>

  <p>Forty-three thousand pounds. That's more than many tradesmen's entire annual profit. Being unreachable for eight hours a day is costing you a second income.</p>

  <h2>Scenario 3: The Emergency Trade Premium</h2>

  <p>If you're a <a href="/ai-receptionist-for-plumbers">plumber</a>, <a href="/ai-receptionist-for-electricians">electrician</a>, <a href="/ai-receptionist-for-locksmiths">locksmith</a>, or <a href="/ai-receptionist-for-gas-engineers">gas engineer</a>, the numbers get worse because emergency work carries a premium.</p>

  <ul>
    <li>Missed calls: <strong>5 per week</strong></li>
    <li>Genuine emergency enquiries: <strong>40%</strong> (2 calls)</li>
    <li>Emergency job value: <strong>£250-500</strong></li>
    <li>Conversion if answered: <strong>80%</strong> (emergencies nearly always convert)</li>
  </ul>

  <p><strong>Lost emergency revenue: £400-800 per week. £20,800-41,600 per year.</strong></p>

  <p>Emergency customers don't leave voicemails. They call the next tradesman immediately. If you miss an emergency call, that job is gone — there is zero chance of recovering it with a callback.</p>

  <h2>The Hidden Costs You're Not Counting</h2>

  <p>The maths above only counts the immediate revenue loss. There are hidden costs that compound:</p>

  <h3>Lost Reviews</h3>
  <p>Every missed job is a Google review you never received. Reviews build your Google rankings. Fewer reviews means lower rankings means fewer future calls. <strong>Missing calls today costs you leads tomorrow.</strong></p>

  <h3>Lost Referrals</h3>
  <p>A customer you never served is a customer who never recommends you to their neighbours, friends, and family. Word of mouth — the most powerful marketing for tradesmen — requires completed jobs to generate referrals.</p>

  <h3>Lost Content</h3>
  <p>If you're using <a href="/ai-marketing-for-tradesmen">AI marketing</a> to turn completed jobs into website content and social media posts, every missed job is content that was never created — a blog post that never ranked, a social post that never built your reputation.</p>

  <h3>The Feast-Or-Famine Cycle</h3>
  <p>The cruelest irony: you miss the most calls during your busiest weeks. Those missed calls represent the work that would have filled your quiet weeks two or three weeks later. <strong>Missing calls during busy periods directly causes quiet periods.</strong></p>

  <h2>The Fix Costs Less Than You Think</h2>

